│ THOUGHT                                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ My previous attempts to patch the file failed because my `sed` patterns were not matching the source code. After inspecting the `PHIHandler` class, I've identified the exact location   │
│ and logic needed to fix the infinite recursion bug.                                                                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The problem lies in the `buildOperands` method of the `PHIHandler` class. When it processes the incoming values for a bundle of PHI nodes, it doesn't correctly handle the case where an │
│ incoming block is the same as the block containing the PHIs (a direct cycle). This leads to infinite recursion in `buildTree_rec`.                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The fix is to add a check right after getting an incoming block. If the incoming block is the same as the PHI's parent block, it means we have a recursive edge. In this case, we should │
│ not try to find the real operands. Instead, we can fill the operand list for this edge with `PoisonValue` and continue to the next incoming edge. This breaks the cycle.                 │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The line `BasicBlock *InBB = Main->getIncomingBlock(I);` appears in both the "fast path" and the general path within `buildOperands`. By using this line as an anchor for a              │
│ substitution, I can patch both loops with a single `sed` command. The command will replace the anchor line with itself, followed by the new checking logic. This ensures the fix is      │
│ applied comprehensively within the `PHIHandler`.                                                                                                                                         │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ ```bash                                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ sed -i 's/BasicBlock \*InBB = Main->getIncomingBlock(I);/BasicBlock *InBB = Main->getIncomingBlock(I);\                                                                                  │
│         if (InBB == Main->getParent()) {\                                                                                                                                                │
│           Operands[I].assign(Phis.size(), PoisonValue::get(Main->getType()));\                                                                                                           │
│           continue;\                                                                                                                                                                     │
│         }/g' ./llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp                                                                                                                           │
│ ```                                                                                                                                                                                      │
